1
00:00:00,100 --> 00:00:03,583
This demo shows OpenShell shared agent memory.

2
00:00:03,533 --> 00:00:10,168
NemoClaw is the reference integration environment, but the reusable capability is the OpenShell memory driver.

3
00:00:10,168 --> 00:00:13,665
We start Redis as the MVP storage backend.

4
00:00:13,665 --> 00:00:18,882
Redis gives us a durable stream quickly, but it stays behind the platform boundary.

5
00:00:18,882 --> 00:00:24,182
Next, OpenShell starts the memory driver and exposes slash v one slash memory.

6
00:00:24,182 --> 00:00:27,764
OpenClaw and Hermes do not get Redis credentials.

7
00:00:27,764 --> 00:00:31,382
They only get the OpenShell endpoint and a workspace scope.

8
00:00:31,382 --> 00:00:36,574
Here is the real-world scenario: release validation for the shared-memory MVP.

9
00:00:36,574 --> 00:00:40,420
Hermes subscribes to release updates before it starts work.

10
00:00:40,420 --> 00:00:44,879
In this MVP, subscribe creates a durable filtered inbox.

11
00:00:44,879 --> 00:00:50,432
The current delivery mode is pull, so the agent later pulls pending events from that inbox.

12
00:00:50,432 --> 00:00:53,401
Now OpenClaw finds a release blocker.

13
00:00:53,401 --> 00:00:59,615
The shared-memory MVP should not be marked demo-ready until the Hermes adapter smoke path has been validated.

14
00:00:59,615 --> 00:01:03,653
OpenClaw publishes that as release dot blocker dot detected.

15
00:01:03,653 --> 00:01:09,771
The event includes a subject, structured content, provenance, visibility, and a schema version.

16
00:01:09,771 --> 00:01:13,653
OpenShell accepts the event and appends it to Redis Streams.

17
00:01:13,653 --> 00:01:20,000
Notice the boundary: Redis stores the stream, but the agent contract remains the OpenShell memory API.

18
00:01:20,000 --> 00:01:24,639
Hermes pulls its subscription inbox and receives the OpenClaw blocker.

19
00:01:24,639 --> 00:01:29,326
This is why the demo has a poll command: it is not an extra query step.

20
00:01:29,326 --> 00:01:32,680
It is pull delivery for a durable subscription.

21
00:01:32,680 --> 00:01:39,326
Future OpenShell drivers can add webhooks, server-sent events, or WebSockets without changing the event schema.

22
00:01:39,326 --> 00:01:43,533
Hermes acknowledges the blocker so it will not be replayed forever.

23
00:01:43,533 --> 00:01:47,536
Hermes then publishes release dot remediation dot planned.

24
00:01:47,536 --> 00:01:58,413
The remediation plan says it will run the Hermes adapter smoke path through OpenShell, validate subscribe, pull, acknowledge, and response publishing, and keep Redis hidden behind the driver boundary.

25
00:01:58,413 --> 00:02:02,055
Finally, OpenClaw queries the remediation plan.

26
00:02:02,055 --> 00:02:07,235
The release handoff is closed without either agent knowing the other's implementation details.

27
00:02:07,235 --> 00:02:12,031
That is the value proposition: a plug-in shared memory driver for agents.

28
00:02:12,031 --> 00:02:18,846
It is durable, scoped, polyglot, auditable, and reusable for future agents beyond OpenClaw and Hermes.

